<paragraph blockId="7.[168,775,749,1200]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">
This species is characterized by having 1 dorsal- fin spine, 7 soft dorsal-fin rays, 4 or 5 anal-fin spines, and 8 or 9 soft anal-fin rays. It can be distinguished from all congeners, except by 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Chaudhuri" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[399,564,973,996]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bagridae" genus="Batasio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merianiensis">
<emphasis box="[399,564,973,996]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">B. merianiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by having an adult color pattern consisting of a dark oblique predorsal bar and dark spot on the lateral of the body, just ventral to the adipose-fin base. This fish occurs in rivers and streams with moderate to swift current and a predominantly rocky bottom; it is less often in slow-flowing streams with a muddy substrate (
<bibRefCitation author="Ng HH &amp; Kottelat M" box="[358,594,1176,1200]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" pagination="495 - 511" refId="ref8596" refString="Ng HH, Kottelat M (2001) A review of the genus Batasio (Teleostei: Bagridae) in Indochina, with the description of B. tigrinus sp. n. from Thailand. Revue Suisse de Zoologie 108 (3): 495 - 511." type="journal article" year="2001">Ng and Kottelat 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
